To make this solution more efficient for handling large amounts of text, we can use memory-mapped files (mmaps) instead of loading the entire contents of `Text1` and `Text2` into memory at once. This allows us to read and process the files in smaller chunks without exceeding available memory.

Here's how you can modify the script to use mmaps:

```matlab
function findUniqueWords(file1, file2)
    %Open the input files as mmaps
    fid1 = mmap('r', file1);
    fid2 = mmap('r', file2);

    %Initialize variables for storing text and word sets
    text1 = [];
    text2 = [];
    words1 = [];
    words2 = [];

    %Loop through files to read in text and store words
    while ~eof(fid1) && ~eof(fid2)
        text1(end+1:end, :) = text1(end, :) + fgetl(fid1);
        text2(end+1:end, :) = text2(end, :) + fgetl(fid2);

        words1(end+1:end, :) = strsplit(lower(text1(end, :)));
        words2(end+1:end, :) = strsplit(lower(text2(end, :)));

        %Remove trailing whitespace from last line of each file
        text1(end, :) = text1(end, :)(1:-1:1);
        text2(end, :) = text2(end, :)(1:-1:1);
    end

    %Close the mmaps and free resources
    close(fid1);
    close(fid2);
    unmap(fid1);
    unmap(fid2);

    %Find unique words in text1 that do not appear in text2
    uniqueWords = setdiff(words1(:), words2(:));

    %Print the unique words
    disp(uniqueWords(:));
end
