To retrieve the username from the JWT (JSON Web Token) in an ASP.NET Core WebAPI, you can follow these steps:

1. Install the `Microsoft.IdentityModel.Tokens` package by running the following command in your project's terminal or command prompt:

   ```
   dotnet add package Microsoft.IdentityModel.Tokens
   ```

2. Add the `AddJwtBearer()` method to the `ConfigureServices()` method of your Startup class to configure JWT authentication:

   ```csharp
   services.AddAuthentication(options =>
   {
       options.DefaultAuthenticateScheme = JwtBearerDefaults.AuthenticationScheme;
       options.DefaultChallengeScheme = JwtBearerDefaults.AuthenticationScheme;
   })
   .AddJwtBearer(options =>
   {
       options.TokenValidationParameters = new TokenValidationParameters
       {
           ValidateIssuerSigningKey = true,
           IssuerSigningKey = new SymmetricSecurityKey(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes("super-secret-key")),
           ValidateIssuer = false,
           ValidateAudience = false
       };
   });
   ```

   In this example, replace "super-secret-key" with your own secret key that will be used to sign and verify the JWT tokens. You can also customize other parameters such as the issuer and audience if needed.

3. Next, add the `[Authorize]` attribute to your controller or action methods to require authentication:

   ```csharp
   [Authorize]
   [Route("api/[controller]/[action]")]
   public IActionResult Get()
   {
       // Retrieve the username from the context
       var username = User.Claims.FirstOrDefault(c => c.Type == ClaimTypes.Name).Value;

       // Return a response
       return Ok();
   }
   ```

